{"cursor":"37462","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=right\n|- colspan=\"2\" | from Hubble Space Telescope October 28, 2005 with\n|sandstorm visible.]] - Chemical species mole fraction - Carbon dioxide\n| 95.32% - Nitrogen\n|  2.7% - Argon\n|  1.6% - Oxygen 1300 ppm - Carbon monoxide 800 ppm - Water vapor 210 ppm -\n|    Nitric oxide 100 ppm - Neon\n|  2.5 ppm - HDO 850 ppb - Krypton 300 ppb - Xenon 80 ppb - Ozone 30 ppb -\n|    Methane\n| 10.5 ppb }\n\n\n'The atmosphere of [[Mars]]' is, like that of Venus, composed mostly of carbon\ndioxide though far thinner. There has been renewed interest in its composition\nsince the detection of traces of methane [http://www.astrobio.net/news/article1651.html Interplanetary\nWhodunit - Methane on Mars], David Tenenbaum, Astrobiology Magazine, NASA, July\n20, 2005. (Note: part one of a four-part series.) Mumma, M. J.; Novak, R. E.; DiSanti, M. A.; Bonev, B. P., [http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-\nbib_query?bibcode=2003DPS....35.1418M&db_key=AST&data_type=HTML&format= \"A\nSensitive Search for Methane on Mars\"] (abstract only). American Astronomical\nSociety, DPS meeting #35, #14.18. that may indicate life but may also be\nproduced by a geochemical process, volcanic or hydrothermal activity. [http-\n://astrobio.net/news/modules.php?op=modload&name=News&file=article&sid=2765&mod-\ne=thread&order=0&thold=0 Making Sense of Mars Methane (June 2008)]\n\nThe atmospheric pressure on the Martian surface averages , about 0.6% of Earth's\nmean sea level pressure of and only .0065% that of Venus's . It ranges from a\nlow of on Olympus Mons's peak to over in the depths of Hellas Planitia. Mars's\natmospheric mass of 25 teratonnes compares to Earth's 5148 teratonnes with a\nscale height of about versus Earth's . The Martian atmosphere is about 95%\ncarbon dioxide, 3% nitrogen, 1.6% argon, and traces of free oxygen, carbon\nmonoxide, water and methane, among other gases, for a mean molar mass of 43.34\ng/mol. Seiff, A. and Kirk,\nD. (1977). [http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1977JGR....82.4364S \"Structure of the\natmosphere of Mars in summer at mid-latitudes\"] (abstract only). Journal of\nGeophysical Research, 82(28):4364â4378. The atmosphere is quite dusty,\ngiving the Martian sky a light brown or orange color when seen from the surface;\ndata from the Mars Exploration Rovers indicate that suspended dust particles\nwithin the atmosphere are roughly 1.5 micrometres across. [http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-\nbib_query?bibcode=2004Sci...306.1753L&db_key=AST&data_type=HTML&format=&high=43-\n9c7b95b425777 Lemmon et al., \"Atmospheric Imaging Results from the Mars\nExploration Rovers: Spirit and Opportunity\"]\n","linknr":1201,"url":"Atmosphere_of_Mars","recorded":1362371875,"links":73,"instances":["geology","chemistry","mars","planet"],"pdf":["http://www-mars.lmd.jussieu.fr/mars/publi/forget_science2004.pdf","http://www-mars.lmd.jussieu.fr/mars/publi/forget_science2004.pdf","http://images.spaceref.com/news/2009/Mumma_et_al_Methane_Mars_wSOM_accepted2.pdf","http://images.spaceref.com/news/2009/Mumma_et_al_Methane_Mars_wSOM_accepted2.pdf","http://esse.engin.umich.edu/psl/PRESS/Mars/NatureNews_2008.pdf","http://esse.engin.umich.edu/psl/PRESS/Mars/NatureNews_2008.pdf","http://www.lpi.usra.edu/meetings/lpsc2010/pdf/2456.pdf","http://www.lpi.usra.edu/meetings/lpsc2010/pdf/2456.pdf","http://www.lpi.usra.edu/meetings/abscicon2010/pdf/5590.pdf","http://www.lpi.usra.edu/meetings/abscicon2010/pdf/5590.pdf","http://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/20090026215_2009024820.pdf","http://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/20090026215_2009024820.pdf","http://www.lpi.usra.edu/meetings/lpsc2011/pdf/2427.pdf","http://www.lpi.usra.edu/meetings/lpsc2011/pdf/2427.pdf","http://mepag.jpl.nasa.gov/reports/MSO_SAG2_Report_MEPAG_29may1.pdf","http://mepag.jpl.nasa.gov/reports/MSO_SAG2_Report_MEPAG_29may1.pdf"],"categories":["Mars","Planetary atmospheres|M